# .cursorrules
# Add this file to the root of your Flutter project (mobile-flutter/)

You are an expert Flutter developer building a production-grade cross-platform mobile app for Android and iOS.

## Stack & Environment
- Flutter stable channel, Dart 3.x
- State management: Riverpod (preferred) — use ConsumerWidget, AsyncNotifier, StateNotifier patterns
- Navigation: go_router
- Dependency injection: Riverpod providers only, no get_it unless specified
- HTTP: dio with interceptors
- Local storage: shared_preferences for simple KV, hive for structured local data
- Backend: Firebase (Firestore, Auth, Storage) unless told otherwise

## Architecture
- Follow feature-first folder structure:
  lib/
  ├── core/           # theme, constants, utils, errors, network
  ├── features/
  │   └── feature_name/
  │       ├── data/       # models, repositories, data sources
  │       ├── domain/     # entities, use cases, repo interfaces
  │       └── presentation/ # screens, widgets, providers
  └── main.dart
- Never put business logic inside widgets
- All API calls go through repository classes, never directly in UI
- Models must have fromJson/toJson, copyWith
- Separate widgets into reusable components in a widgets/ subfolder

## Dart Code Rules
- Always use const constructors where possible
- Use named parameters for all custom widgets
- Never use dynamic types — always type explicitly
- Use sealed classes / freezed for state modeling
- Handle all nullable types explicitly, no ! operator unless absolutely justified with a comment
- Prefer async/await over .then() chains
- Use Result<T> or Either<Failure, T> pattern for error handling

## Flutter UI Rules
- Use LayoutBuilder and MediaQuery for responsive layouts — never hardcode pixel values
- Use SafeArea on all top-level screens
- Theme everything through ThemeData — no hardcoded colors or font sizes anywhere in widgets
- Use flutter_screenutil for font/size scaling across devices
- Avoid deeply nested widget trees — extract into methods or separate widget classes above 3 levels deep

## Cross-platform (Android + iOS) Rules
- Always test logic for both platforms mentally — never assume Android-only behavior
- For platform-specific code use Platform.isAndroid / Platform.isIOS checks or method channels
- Permissions: use permission_handler package, always handle denied/permanently denied states
- For camera, file picker, notifications — always implement both Android and iOS permission flows
- pubspec.yaml: always add both android and ios permission keys when using native features
- Gradle: target SDK 34+, minSdk 21
- iOS: deployment target iOS 13.0+

## Packages — Prefer These
- State: flutter_riverpod, riverpod_annotation
- Navigation: go_router
- Networking: dio
- Serialization: json_serializable, freezed
- Storage: hive_flutter, shared_preferences
- Auth: firebase_auth, google_sign_in
- DB: cloud_firestore
- Images: cached_network_image
- Permissions: permission_handler
- Env vars: flutter_dotenv
- UI utilities: flutter_screenutil, gap
- Charts: fl_chart
- PDF: printing, pdf

## Code Generation
- Always add the required build_runner annotations when using freezed or json_serializable
- Remind to run: flutter pub run build_runner build --delete-conflicting-outputs

## What NOT to do
- Don't use GetX for anything
- Don't use setState in complex screens — use Riverpod
- Don't put API keys in source code
- Don't hardcode strings visible to users — use a constants file
- Don't generate placeholder/TODO logic and leave it — always implement or explicitly mark with // TODO: [reason]
- Don't use deprecated Flutter APIs — check Flutter 3.x compatibility
- Don't nest Scaffold inside Scaffold